  <h2>Why Dental Health Matters</h2>
  <p>
    Dental disease is one of the most common — and most preventable — conditions in dogs and cats. By age three, most pets show signs of periodontal disease. Left untreated, oral bacteria can enter the bloodstream and cause damage to the heart, kidneys, and liver.
  </p>
  <p>
    At All About Pets, we include a thorough oral exam as part of every wellness visit, and we provide professional cleanings and extractions when needed.
  </p>

  <h2>Signs Your Pet May Need Dental Care</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Bad breath (halitosis) that persists beyond a day or two</li>
    <li>Difficulty chewing, dropping food, or favoring one side of the mouth</li>
    <li>Visible tartar buildup — yellow or brown deposits on the teeth</li>
    <li>Red, swollen, or bleeding gums</li>
    <li>Pawing at the mouth or face</li>
    <li>Drooling more than usual</li>
    <li>Reluctance to chew toys or play with the mouth</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What Our Dental Services Include</h2>
  <p>
    Our dental care services cover the full spectrum of your pet's oral health needs:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Oral examinations</strong> — thorough visual and manual assessment at every wellness visit</li>
    <li><strong>Professional cleanings</strong> — ultrasonic scaling and polishing above and below the gumline, performed under safe anesthesia</li>
    <li><strong>Dental X-rays</strong> — to identify problems below the surface that can't be seen visually</li>
    <li><strong>Extractions</strong> — when a tooth is too damaged or infected to save, removal relieves pain and prevents spread</li>
    <li><strong>Home care guidance</strong> — brushing techniques, dental chews, and other tools to slow plaque buildup between visits</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The Benefits of Regular Dental Checkups</h2>
  <p>
    Catching dental disease early makes a meaningful difference in treatment outcomes, cost, and your pet's comfort. A professional cleaning can dramatically reduce inflammation and prevent tooth loss. Many pets become visibly more energetic and comfortable after a dental procedure — sometimes their owners didn't realize how much pain they were living with.
  </p>

